editorial:
**Idea — factorial decomposition**: Among n! permutations, the first (n-1)! start with the smallest available digit, the next (n-1)! with the second smallest, etc. So the leading digit is `digits[(k-1) / (n-1)!]` — remove it and recurse on the remainder.

```javascript
function getPermutation(n, k) {
  const fact = [1];
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) fact.push(fact[i - 1] * i);
  const digits = [];
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) digits.push(i);
  let rem = k - 1;
  let out = '';
  for (let i = n; i >= 1; i--) {
    const block = fact[i - 1];
    const idx = Math.floor(rem / block);
    out += digits[idx].toString();
    digits.splice(idx, 1);
    rem = rem % block;
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(n²) due to splice. **Space**: O(n).

